```
There are two different data types in the python programming language:

```
1. Numeric type: This is a series of numbers. It also includes integers, complex numbers, and floats.
2. String type:This is a series of characters.It includes a string constant and string variable. 
3. Boolean type: This is true or false.It is often confused with the number 1, as it is just represented as a number.
4. Symbol type: This is a special character to indicate the beginning and end of a number and boolean value, but not the space or tab character.
5. Tuple type: This is a combination of different data types into a tuple (order is the same as the number of values).  ```

It was not surprising to anyone in the class when Mary, one of our shyest students, raised her hand to ask a question in her teacher’s English class. When the teacher called on her, Mary had an incredulous look on her face. Without thinking, the teacher replied by asking, “Well, Mary, what question do you have for me?” Without hesitation, Mary responded to the “What do you want?” question with “I … want nothing.” This bizarre incident, which was so strange to most people that they remembered it after nearly a half century, has been on my mind and in my heart for all these years.

Ironically, by the time she was two years old, Mary knew all her numbers. Mary was born three months prematurely and it was the doctor’s prediction that she would be blind, deaf, and mentally retarded. She did have some developmental problems, but not to such an extreme degree. After a year of intensive therapy, Mary’s parents brought her to Montana, where they felt she would be more likely to receive the adequate special help she needed.
It was in school that Mary experienced the initial rejection that she would encounter throughout her life. She and her two siblings were brought to school each day via the school bus, so as not to inhibit Mary’s learning process. In second grade, Mary’s teacher told her that she would try to find a way to include her in the classroom. By the end of the year, Mary could not function in her classroom. She was taken out of class each day and sent to another school room.

When I met Mary on the campus of Montana State University, in the early 1970s, Mary was working a full-time job, earning an Associate’s Degree for her job on the production line of a large dairy corporation, and raising a teenage son on her own. For all her physical health issues—Mary used a wheelchair due to spinal problems and could not use her left arm beyond a few minutes at a time because of severe arthritis—she possessed a great sense of humor and a loving heart. Mary was a person who was as kind and humble as can be, never seeking attention
